[3] Insecurity disrupts control effort
Date: Tue 26 Nov 2019 7:04 AM EST
Source: Nasdaq, Reuters report [abridged, edited]
https://www.nasdaq.com/articles/who-unicef-evacuate-76-staff-from-ebola-teams-in-congo-due-to-insecurity-2019-11-26


The World Health Organization (WHO) and the UN Children's Fund (UNICEF) on [Tue 26 Nov 2019] evacuated dozens of their staff working on the Ebola epidemic from the town of Beni in DRC due to the worsening security situation. Rebels believed to belong to the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) killed 8 people in an overnight raid on [Sun 24 Nov 2019].

Residents angry at the perceived inaction of both the government and a UN peacekeeping mission then set fire to the mayor's office and several UN buildings on [Mon 25 Nov 2019]. At least 2 people were killed in clashes with police.

WHO spokesman Christian Lindmeier told a news briefing in Geneva that 49 non-essential staff were flown on Tuesday morning [26 Nov 2019] to the eastern city of Goma, where they will continue working. "71 remain on the spot at this point to ensure as good as possible or at least the minimum support to the Ebola response," Lindmeier said. "The frustration, the anger of the population on the ground is very much understandable. But we need law and order restored to carry out vital operations," he said.

The UN Children's Fund (UNICEF) has temporarily relocated 27 staff, leaving 12 in Beni, spokeswoman Marixie Mercado said.

Dr Michael Ryan, executive director of the WHO Health Emergencies Programme, said on [Fri 22 Nov 2019] that about 360 people were at potential risk of Ebola after contact with an infected person in eastern Congo, yet many of them were out of reach due to clashes and insecurity.

"The violence has to stop, we have enough areas where we cannot go due to violence, military violence, or rebel violence going on. So this is very bad for the Ebola response," Lindmeier told the briefing.

There have been 3303 cases of Ebola, including 2199 deaths, in the outbreak that was declared in August 2018. The WHO declared it an international emergency in July 2019.

[byline: Stephanie Nebehay; additional reporting by Marina Depetris in Geneva; editing by Catherine Evans, Angus MacSwan]

